We recommended and the management agreed to:
Direct the GSO and the Municipal Accountant to be guided by COA Circular No. 2020-006 in conducting physical count of PPE, preparation of necessary reports, reconciliation procedures, and recording in the books;
Direct the Inventory Committee to prepare and submit the RPCPPE upon the completion of the physical inventory;
Organize periodic disposal of unserviceable property to prevent further deterioration and loss in recoverable value, clear out hazardous waste or materials and optimize use of storage spaces; and
Timely submit Inventory and Inspection Report of Unserviceable Property (IIRUP).
Also, we recommended and the management agreed as well, that the Municipal Accountant prepare the JEV to derecognize the PPE accounts from the books upon receipt of the IIRUP from GSO.

We recommended and the management agreed to:
Intensify efforts in implementing the PPAs and optimally utilize its funds contained in the LDRRMF Investment Plan, and;
Evaluate the unimplemented PPAs in accordance to their attainability, and reprogram those to practicable ones in the subsequent year that is still responsive to the needs of its constituents and the LGU with respect to disaster prevention, preparedness, response and recovery for other calamities in the midst of the pandemic, and optimally implement those PPAs immediately.

To strengthen the risk management capabilities of the Municipal Government and enable it to manage its vulnerabilities in the event of disruptive events, we recommended and the management agreed that the Local Chief Executive (LCE) institutionalize the PSCP by creating a working group that will perform the following activities:
conduct risk assessment;
identify critical processes and functions;
determine scenarios that may disrupt normal operation;
conduct risk analysis and impact analysis;
formulate the PSCP based on the identified risks on critical processes and functions and its related steps to be followed to eliminate, if not mitigate, the impact of the determined disruptions following the prescribed template and be guided by the PSCP guidebook; and
submit plan to the MDRRMO for review, to the LCE for approval, and to the Sangguniang Bayan for the passage of a resolution to institutionalize the PSCP.
We also recommended and the management agreed as well to improve their monitoring of operational requirements like the submission of PSCP.

